article.description:
Doug Christie had 23 points and eight
rebounds and Bobby Jackson scored 21 points as the shorthanded
Sacramento Kings won for the 10th time in 11 games, beating the
Denver Nuggets 98-77 Friday night.
article.headline: Nuggets fall for 12th straight time at Arco Arena
article.linkText: Short-handed Kings have few problems with Nuggets
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Rick Adelman would have loved to bench several of his regulars and empty the Sacramento Kings' bench.
Jackson

Christie

Given the circumstances, however, the coach simply shut his mouth. Doug Christie had 23 points and eight rebounds and Bobby Jackson scored 21 points as the short-handed Kings won for the 10th time in 11 games, beating the Denver Nuggets 98-77 Friday night. Chris Webber had 17 points and 11 rebounds as Sacramento remained unbeaten in 11 home games despite suiting up the NBA-minimum eight players for the fourth time this season. The Pacific Division leaders kept up their improbable roll in dire circumstances by beating lowly Denver for the second time in three days, but it was a sloppy, uninspiring game featuring 44 turnovers. The Kings were lousy for long stretches -- but they still were plenty good enough to win. "These types of games, I stopped talking about it after a while,'' said Adelman, who has prodded his tiny roster to a five-game winning streak despite being unable to practice without assistant coach Terry Porter playing. "We've got to understand what's going on with our injury situation, and just let a few things slide. We got a win out of it, and we're playing much better teams in the next few days.'' The Kings hit 12 3-pointers and recovered from a dismal second quarter to beat Denver for the sixth straight time. Christie also had six assists and four steals while hitting five 3-pointers. James Posey scored 22 points for the Nuggets, who lost their fifth straight. Denver hasn't won at Arco Arena in 12 tries since Jan. 7, 1997. Because Adelman wanted to rest Webber, Vlade Divac and Christie for Sunday's game in San Antonio, Jackson was forced to play the final four minutes, even though "I hated putting him back in there,'' Adelman said. "I hated going back in there,'' Jackson said with a grin. "I was done for the night, but when we've only got eight guys, I don't mind helping out. I got behind the 3-point line, and I stood way out there. I wasn't touching anything.'' The Kings played with their usual freedom and outstanding flow in the opening minutes, shooting 63 percent in the first quarter and leading by 19 early in the second, but both teams then went into prolonged funks. Sacramento committed turnovers on six straight possessions while scoring just two points in the final 6:16 before halftime -- but Denver wasn't much better, scoring just eight points in several minutes of terrible basketball for both teams. "The effort was there once again from our young team, but our inability to make shots just allows teams to get out on the break,'' Denver coach Jeff Bzdelik said. "We just can't put it down, even from the free throw line. Free throws, layups and missed open shots have been our Achilles' heel all year long.'' Christie hit consecutive 3-pointers in the third quarter as the Kings got back to a healthy lead. Sacramento held the Nuggets scoreless for nearly five minutes in the fourth quarter. Juwan Howard had 11 points and 10 rebounds for Denver, which has its second five-game losing streak in a month -- with a three-game winning streak sandwiched in between. "The Kings are very effective,'' Posey said. "The guys that are playing, they're playing smart and stepping up. That's a sign of the depth that the Kings have.'' The Kings have been without Mike Bibby and Mateen Cleaves all season, while Scot Pollard has been out for a month with a stress fracture in his back that doesn't seem to be getting better. All-Star Peja Stojakovic recently returned to Sacramento after traveling to Yugoslavia to consult with a specialist on the inflamed tissue in his heel. Stojakovic has missed eight games with the injury, while key reserve Hedo Turkoglu has missed five games with a sprained wrist. To top it all off, Lawrence Funderburke, the Kings' rarely-used backup big man, missed his second straight game with inflamed tissue and tendinitis in his left foot. Improbably, the Kings have thrived with eight healthy players -- and just five who were with Sacramento last season. What's more, the Kings have played 22 games -- more than any NBA team so far this season. The Kings have three straight road games next week, while Denver plays its next two at home. Game notes
Nuggets rookie Nene Hilario sat out with a strained neck. He'll be re-evaluated on Saturday before Denver's home game against Indiana. ... Ryan Bowen had seven steals for Denver. ... Twice in the first half, Sacramento's Gerald Wallace knocked over folding chairs while making dangerous leaps to save balls that were going out of bounds. Both times, he was successful. ... Denver's Donnell Harvey went 1-of-6 from the free throw line. He also missed his last six field goal attempts.
